"social_media": "Instagram: @alexiacantore @kagayama.js\nLinkedIn: https://ca.linkedin.com/in/alexiacantore AND https://www.linkedin.com/in/jacob-steer-kagayama-93b06534b/",
"work_email": "alexiacantoredesigns@gmail.com AND jacobktsteer@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Hum. Helping U move ",
"project_description": "Hum is a collaborative packaging design and branding project that focuses on designing for the elderly to promote healthy living. Hum is dedicated to providing products that promote healthy mobility and active living. through high contrast colours, highly legible text, and refined graphics. The product themselves designed for providing support and mobility aids proving the importance of exercising safely. Hum also includes a partnership with an organization #oldernotover where $1 spent on the product is donated back to reducing stereotypes about aging life. ",
"bio": "Jacob and Alexia work collaboratively to find design solutions that are easily digestible, approachable, fun, and educational. The goal is to create inclusive design that proves the importance of designing for all. By looking to promote healthy living, this caters to a wide demographic of people also contributing to a global enterprise. ",
"comments": "Find us and our work in room 654 on the 6th floor of OCAD U's main building at 100 McCaul street. "
}

"social_media": "Instagram: @alisonrepetski.gd\nLinkedIn: www.linkedin.com/in/alison-repetski-49b9a5263\n",
"work_email": "projects@alisonrepetski.ca",
"project_name": "",
"project_description": "Commensality is the union of food, togetherness and space. A turn from the biological need for nourishment, to the social need for togetherness. \"Join Me at the Dining Table\" is a unique and interactive installation piece that guides viewers through four foundational elements of commensality, that is: memory, tradition, faith and invitation. Viewers are also encouraged to engage in dinner conversation as they move through the dining experience, generating commensality in real time.\n\nCommensality is an inescapable and important factor of the human experience, and even so it is a ritual that is becoming lost (or rare) due to the widescale loneliness and isolation epidemic. \"Join Me At the Dining Table\" asks viewers to reflect on the meaning of their own dining table. How has it been a factor in the development of their identity? Is there more at the dining table than they are letting themselves experience?",
"bio": "Alison Repetski is a Toronto based Graphic Designer with a specific interest in digital and publication design. From time to time, Alison blends the digital with the real world, building tactile objects meant to be physically experienced and engaged with. She hopes that the end user connects with her design work in a way that leaves them thinking, even long after engaging with the work. In an age largely driven by the commercial, Alison hopes that her practice will motivate change and social good.",
"comments": "Please use jpeg titled, 'joinme' as the first image if possible. I have a vimeo link of my video since the file size is too large https://vimeo.com/manage/videos/1077970403 let me know if that won't work. \n\nI also have a publication link: https://heyzine.com/flip-book/076dc0ef0a.html"
}

"work_email": "anischitasaha64@gmail.com",
"project_name": "",
"project_description": "What if design could help people heal, navigate the world, and feel seen? Anischita Saha (@jellybeanani) is a Graphic Design student whose work is rooted in accessibility, sustainability and care. Her projects, like Cafune, a reimagined shampoo and conditioner system for visually impaired users, and Sip Well, a freeze-dried smoothie for those healing from eating disorders, are designed to meet real needs with empathy and intention. "I do struggle with a disability myself, and I think that experience sort of changed me and pushed me to make work that actually helps people in the real world." By centering the lived experiences of others, Anischita is rethinking how design can serve - not just sell. Each project is a thoughtful gesture toward a more inclusive world.",
"bio": "Anischita Saha (Ani) is a Toronto-based graphic designer and animator in her fourth year at OCAD University, majoring in Graphic Design. Her creative practice spans package design, branding, motion graphics, and typeface design, with a strong focus on accessibility and sustainability. Ani is passionate about crafting thoughtful, impactful work that fosters connection—whether through collaborative group projects or self-directed explorations. Her playful curiosity carries into her personal life as well: when she's not designing, you’ll likely find her sculpting with clay, snorkeling, or hanging out with her beloved collection of frog plushies (one of which has attended every single class). 🐸",
"comments": ""
}

"website": "https://avacvit.format.com/work",
"social_media": "Instagram: @avacvit",
"work_email": "avacvit.design@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Foreign Forms - Research Publication. Fallen Branches - Data Visualization. Sororal Itineraries - Editorial",
"project_description": "I focus on the built environment, memory, and our climate within my work. I use these ideas to communicate how consequential and vital they are within our society, to maintain and protect aspects of the natural within a manufactured world. \n\nForeign Forms is a research publication that studies memory within architecture. It explores structures that have found ways of storing, destroying, or unintentionally preserving memory within the initial space. Foreign Forms intends to create a way to regard collective, personal, and historical memory within architecture—how places form meaning without requiring ornamental features or famous recognition, but instead how communities and individuals find meaning within a building.\n\nFallen Branches explores turning data into a physical artifact representing the increase/decrease in forest area between 1990 and 2020. Each branch represents a country that has either developed positive or negative transformations. \n\nSororal travel itineraries explore creating guides that connect to Sororal’s mission of advocating gender equality and combating gender-based violence through travel. I developed guides that communicated their ethos of familiarity and togetherness with playful colours, illustrations and layouts.",
"bio": "I view graphic design as a tool to share and understand the world around me. I practice editorial, print, and illustrative design, focusing on simplicity, community, and self. Our environment and sustainability are factors that I hold close to my design process and philosophy. They inspire me to slow down and be more thoughtful in my approach to life. ",
"comments": ""
}

"completion_time": "4/26/25 0:36:59",
"email": "pundziusavril@ocadu.ca",
"name": "Avril Pundzius",
"modified_time": "",
"preferred_name": "Avril Pundzius",
"pronouns": "she/her;",
"website": "https://pundziusavril.myportfolio.com/",
"social_media": "Instagram: @pundzius\nbluesky: @poissond-avril.bsky.social",
"work_email": "pundziusavril@gmail.com",
"project_name": "project 1: 70 Days of Typography // project 2: The Tarantula Hawk, an informational zine",
"project_description": "70 Days of Typography was a project in which I designed 70 different versions of the ampersand character as an exercise in type design and exploration. I chose to limit myself to designing these using only pencil and paper as a way to incorporate my personal sketching process, but also to push my design skills without the help of digital tools. I tried to balance both designs that were more illustrative and abstract, as well as some that could later be expanded into a full typeface.\n\nMy project on the tarantula hawk wasp is about portraying insects, specifically stinging hymenoptera (bees, wasps, ants), in a more empathetic and positive light. An area of debate of my topic that interested me was how insects are generally perceived and treated by people; I wanted to explore and challenge negative vs positive conceptions of these animals compared to others.\nThe goal of this project was to challenge the usually negative knee-jerk reaction towards insects and to instead foster a different kind of relationship towards them, whether it be fascination, respect, neutrality or other, to lead towards an understanding of their importance in our natural world. My initial project concept was a series of posters depicting various insects from the Schmidt pain index accompanied by the descriptions of their stings from the index and illustrative visual representations of these colourful descriptions, but I pivoted my outcome to accomplish my goal through a series of informational, explorational zines that can fold out into larger decorative posters.",
"bio": "I'm Avril, a graphic designer and illustrator from Montréal, currently based in Toronto. I work mainly by transposing analog textures and techniques into a digital space. Retro poster art is something that inspires me to find ways to combine my background in illustration with my graphic design practice and has developed my taste for type and type design.",
"comments": ""
}

This project focuses on developing a unified digital wayfinding system using dynamic information and real-time updates to make navigation easy and convenient for users across the region.",
  "bio": "I am a multidisciplinary designer, content creator, and urbanist based in Toronto with a background in fine arts. I am passionate about connecting audiences to complex ideas, stories, and systems by making them easy to understand.",
  "comments": ""
}

"project_name": "see the trees / collection of publications, series of workshops and website",
"project_description": "“see the trees” is a collection of design artifacts that emerged from workshops focused on unlearning plant blindness, the phenomenon where humans don’t notice plants and trees around them and instead see them as a background or “stage setting” for animal activity. Each workshop is unique and follows different methods of making the design artifact, including collaborating on the design, each person arranging the order of the spreads and an asynchronous version. Together, the workshops were compiled into a toolkit that is available for everyone to follow at home and try facilitating their own workshop on unlearning plant blindness!",
"bio": "Dana Keselman is a graphic designer based in Tkaronto. Her work centres around humans’ relationship with nature and involves the community in learning together. Dana has exhibited work at the OCADU Open House (2024), Final Thesis Exhibition at the Ada Slaight Gallery (2024) and now the 110th Annual Gradex! ",
"comments": ""
}

contents.content_html:
see the trees

becoming one organism
feb 4th 2025. grange park
group of 4, some friends, some meeting for
the first time. small lecture was given on plant.
blindness then each participant chose a tree
to learn about. through the use of a dispos-
able film camera, drawing, and reflection each
person learned something new about grange
park. post workshop, spreads were designed
by me with the materials from workshop and
participants were instructed to arrange to their
liking. each artifact is unique.

feb 4 20 feb 4 2025

= Lecom

=

q,

or

workshop by

anisi

dana keselman

there are so many trees

feb 15 2025. street in belleville

group of 3, all friends on a getaway from the
city. through the snow storm, the friends
posed in-front of trees, tying humour with
their love of nature. the group gathered and
designed 5 single page riso prints, later sewed
together in a vellum envelope.

trees, childhood and growth

march 17 2025. north york

group of 2, my parents. learning new things
about my parents, we recognize the ways
nature was incorporated in their lives through-
out their childhood to now, as a way to unlearn
plant blindness. designed by me, the spreads
follow the interview. the first column being
russian (their first language) and second, an
english translation.

the study of trees

march 28th 2025

asynchronous, 7 contacted/ 3 submitted, all
ocadu faculty. a final ode to studying at ocadu
and an appreciation for everything I've learned
in the past 4 years from my professors. faculty
were given an assignment brief to acknow!-
edge the trees in their lives and reflect. in-
structions were to design 8-12 pages and drop.
them off in the 6th floor. the signatures were
later combined in a bound volume. participants
include: craig rodmore, brennan kelly and
richard hunt.

plant blindness toolkit

dec 2024- april 2025

one person, me.

a personal reflection and collection of all the
information i've learned in the past 4 months
about plant blindness and how to facilitate
the workshops.

"project_name": "1. Zestyra Kombucha- Package Design 2. How to Personal Shop: A Survival Guide- PC Express Edition- Book Design 3. SMISKI: OCADU Series: Package Design",
"project_description": "Zestyra Kombucha: Created for Packaging Design 2: Design for Good, Zestyra Kombucha, a proudly all-Canadian brand crafted with only natural and organic ingredients grown in this country. More than just a refreshing and healthy beverage, Zestyra embodies a 'Design for Good' ethos, inviting consumers to join the 'Buy Canadian Movement' and actively support our nation amidst global events. Zestyra Kombucha tells the stories of local Ontario farmers and their impacts in Ontario's agriculture, sharing their story on each of our bottles with the produce and herbs they are most known for.\n\nHow to Personal Shop: A Survival Guide- PC Express Edition: Created for Editorial Design: Contemp Issu: Labour, this book contains a funny take on personal shopping through Loblaws stores. It contains a step by step guide on how to complete an order, with illustrations of fruits reenacting the tasks. This book can transform the mundane task of personal shopping into an entertaining adventure, offering both practical guidance and a much-needed dose of humor for anyone who's ever worked as a personal shopper. \n\nSMISKI: OCADU Series: Being an extension off of Editorial Design: Contemp Issu: Bootleg, this special Smiski packaging showcases a creative collaboration with OCAD University (OCAD U). Taking the beloved Japanese blind box phenomenon to a fresh, local level, this 'OCAD U Series' playfully reimagines the lives of OCAD U students through the charmingly quirky Smiski figures and their packaging.",
"bio": "Delusha Wanigasuriya embraces the challenges of creating diverse art through various mediums and exploring innovative approaches. Growing up in Toronto's Regent Park, she was surrounded by extensive artwork, which inspired her to create her own. She enjoys creating artwork that has meaning behind it and expressing herself as a designer.",
"comments": ""
}

"project_name": "My Hometown is Under Attack & Ruïns (Installation, Animation, Poster Design)",
"project_description": "My Hometown is Under Attack\nThis project was created specifically for GradEx 110. It expands upon my earlier analog animation project, Ruïns, which depicted the destruction of buildings in Ukraine caused by Russian Forces. Through this work, I aim to capture the broader devastation of the ongoing Russian-Ukrainian War. As headlines and social media coverage of the war fade from public attention, this project serves as a poignant reminder that the war—and its human cost—continue.\nThese animations are not solely about destroyed structures or their material loss; they are a tribute to the people who once brought these places to life. This made the recent attacks on my hometown of Sumy on April 13th and 18th feel even more personal, reigniting deep anger and an urgent need to speak out. GradEx provides a powerful platform to share this message and honour those affected.\nPlease visit my My Hometown is Under Attack display to learn more and reflect with me.",
"bio": "Dima (he/him) is a Toronto-based graphic designer with experience in print media, brand identity, packaging design, and social media design. His recent work has focused on topics such as urban history and preservation, culture, and social justice. Dima holds a Bachelor of Design from OCAD University in Toronto, ON, and a diploma in Business Administration from the University of Regina.",
"comments": "For the image on the first slide of the carousel, you can use the PNG, and the second slide can be a video. Also, for the website, can I please email you GIFS of my animations because that's how they are meant to be displayed?"
}

"website": "https://whoismiaaa.myportfolio.com/",
"social_media": "Instagram: @who.is.miaaa",
"work_email": "who.is.miaaa@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Reframing the Female Gaze: From Classical Art to Modern Media",
"project_description": "The GradEx work begins with a question that has haunted the history of visual culture: Why do the same images of women, passive, perfected, and posed, continue to repeat across centuries? Tracing a visual timeline from 17th to 19th century academic and salon traditions to today’s beauty magazines and social media aesthetics, this body of work reveals how entrenched ideals of femininity continue to shape how women are seen and represented.\n\nGuided by feminist critique and research, the work includes artist books, posters, prints, and postcards. Using both traditional and digital techniques, gel print transfers, collage, and hand-crafted textures are layered with digital design tools to create reproductions that expose the visual patterns that have persisted over time. These reproductions are not mere copies, but reimaginings that question the authority and legacy of historical imagery.\n\nBy merging analogue and contemporary media, the work explores how reproduction techniques can both expose and resist inherited narratives. It is not only a critique, but an effort to reclaim space for alternative representations, creating images that are more truthful, human, and free. This is a call to see differently and move beyond the gaze that has defined women for far too long. Through this body of work, women’s stories and bodies are reclaimed and reimagined, not as objects, but as subjects of their own power.",
"bio": "Emiliya Volchenko is a Toronto-based graphic designer, visual artist, and photographer. Her practice blends traditional and digital media, rooted in storytelling, emotion, and concept-driven design. She explores themes of femininity, mental health, and identity through editorial design, experimental typography, photography, and interactive media to craft compelling visual narratives.",
"comments": ""
}

"work_email": "floratam02@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Ceramics (1 - gateway, 2 - laptop, 3 - flasks), Prints/Printmaking (4 - didn't i? 5 - cigar-rat?), Photography/Zine (6 - image collector)",
"project_description": "CERAMICS WORK 1 - gateway, 2024 stoneware, glaze description for WORK 1 Gateway is my attempt at creating something that is both beautiful yet functional - it is sculpture and shelf at the same time. While the front is adorned with mirrored, yet not-exactly-symmetrical motifs, the back features space for shelving for your smallest, most prized possessions (a business at the front, party in the back type deal). WORK 2 - laptop, 2024 stoneware, underglaze, glaze, ceramic decals description for WORK 2 Laptop is simply a recreation of my everyday laptop that I have used throughout my entire undergrad, in ceramic form. WORK 3 - flasks, 2024 - 2025 slip cast stoneware, glaze, ceramic decals description for WORK 3 Starting from the same form over and over again, I employ a variety of surface techniques and designs to see the many different ways in which I can transform this singular object, creating my collection of Flasks that feel like they belong in the same family, but each have their own voice, remaining distinct from each other. _________ PRINTMAKING WORK 4 - didn't i?, 2024 intaglio print WORK 5 - cigar-rat?, 2024 linoleum relief print description for WORK 4 + 5 In my printmaking practice, I am constantly drawn to depicting animals inspired by my online browsing habits. I take inspiration from memes that juxtapose cute and funny animal pictures with ironic text captions to create whole new layers of meaning and context. _________ PHOTOGRAPHY WORK 6 - image collector, 2024 set of zines description for WORK 6 In this work, I seek to reflect upon the ever present and ongoing shift from physical to digital archives, as well as the relationship that we, as casual archivists, have with these newer methods of collecting. Using the built in search feature in the photos app, I look through, sort and organize the images which I have captured in my everyday life into recurring subjects, compiling them into a small collection of zines to create tangible artifacts that allow me to browse through my digital collection in a physical manner. ",
"bio": "Flora Tam is a multidisciplinary artist working in ceramics, photography, and most recently, printmaking. With a background in graphic design serving as a guiding light for ventures into new mediums, her ever-evolving practice is centred around a love for the human experience, collecting, and creating play in the everyday. ",
"comments": "I do not have a professional looking headshot, I hope the selfie is good enough, sorry in advance! Also hope that the descriptions are adequate, unsure if I was supposed to write whole artist statements for each individual piece. </3 Thank you for putting this together!"
}

"social_media": "Instagram: @planetfran/@fwancine\nLinkedIn: Francine Guilalas",
"work_email": "guilalasfrancine@gmail.com",
"project_name": "in search of",
"project_description": "\"In Search Of\" is a culminating body of work that explores the damsel-in-distress trope and its impact on missing persons cases through its role as the ideal victim. Francine's video essay, \"Stitching the Invisible\", explains this connection and documents her process of cross-stitching a portrait of Kevin Lim, an act that deepened her understanding of the trope’s impact. Accompanying the video and cross-stitch portrait are two books: one shares the same title as the video and serves as its full transcription; the other, \"The Solved/The Unsolved\", contrasts Canada’s solved and unsolved missing persons cases to highlight the real consequences of idealized victimhood.",
"bio": "Francine Guilalas is a graphic designer who's work is driven by a deep interest in how stories take shape through data and design. She often draw from archives, cultural references, and systems of information to create pieces that invite people to look a little closer. For Francine, design is the ultimate tool for storytelling and critique. Her work has been displayed at Ada Slaight Gallery for \"Project: Visual Explainer (2022)\", and the Fall Term Thesis exhibit (2024).",
"comments": ""
}

contents.title: sound_form_association_experiment_liam-kuzma-hunt.jpg
contents.content_html:
Research & Aesthtetic Planning

Abstraction process

ABSTRACTIONS
FULL PROCESS

Each composition is a visual representation of a
musical number by Fleeting Colours. To construct
these abstractions, | began by a consideration of
multi-sensory descriptive language; words which not
only describe form or colour, but also sound qualities
and tactile sensations. Simple words such as soft,
sharp, light, faded, deep etc. create intersensory
associations which | use to construct the formal

and textural qualities of my compositions. This
“associative synaesthesia" serves as the foundational
element throughout my brand design.

The colours within these abstractions were determined
through close analysis of tonal qualities within the
music. Varying melodic characteristics, such as

the clarity of tone, richness, warmth, brightness

etc. dictated the hue, tone, shade and saturation of
colours within each piece.

Colours were not only decided by these associations
but also as representations of personally experienced
aesthetics conjured by the sound. | wanted to

reflect feelings produced by specific relationships
among instrumental and vocal elements through the
organization of colours in proximity to one another.
The placement of colour to form similar relationships
was structured by the organization of visual elements
within the composition.

Fleeting colours 40

Abstraction process

Continuing to stay honest to the music by letting

it inform my creative decision making, | decided to
organize my composition through the perceived
layering of sounds within the music. Determining
background, foreground and middle-ground within
the musical composition helped me to organize my
associated forms, colours and textures. The space
surrounding my abstractions was determined by
the environment produced by the music, acoustical
effects, and base tones.

The blending of various musical elements, an
identifying characteristic of Fleeting Colours’
music, was reflected through the merging of
compositional layers. Areas where many visual
elements overlap to the point of chaotic simplicity
depict Fleeting Colours’ tendency to blend musical
qualities creating periodic blanketing of sounds

Research & Aesthtetic Flanning

The final component to my compositions was
determining and representing rhythm. This was
largely achieved with textures. Textures within
forms, and created by forms in relation to one another,
mimic rhythmic qualities of pattern and repetition.

The shifting pattern of scenes is meant to
express the essence of each song without a linear
organization. By considering the impact of the
emotional synergism between visual stimuli and
the auditory effects of the music, | will begin to find
synchronicities of colour and form to dictate the
aesthetic qualities of my future designs.

a1 Fleeting colours

the musical composition helped me to organize my
associated forms, colours and textures. The space
surrounding my abstractions was determined by
the environment produced by the music, acoustical
effects, and base tones.

The blending of various musical elements, an
identifying characteristic of Fleeting Colours’
music, was reflected through the merging of
compositional layers. Areas where many visual
elements overlap to the point of chaotic simplicity
depict Fleeting Colours’ tendency to blend musical
qualities creating periodic blanketing of sounds

Research & Aesthtetic Flanning

The final component to my compositions was
determining and representing rhythm. This was
largely achieved with textures. Textures within
forms, and created by forms in relation to one another,
mimic rhythmic qualities of pattern and repetition.

The shifting pattern of scenes is meant to
express the essence of each song without a linear
organization. By considering the impact of the
emotional synergism between visual stimuli and
the auditory effects of the music, | will begin to find
synchronicities of colour and form to dictate the
aesthetic qualities of my future designs.

a1 Fleeting colours

"project_name": "Regarding The Aging Female",
"project_description": "Regarding The Aging Female is a physical archive that captures evidence of our culture’s collective attitude towards aging women*. Disseminated across a current total of 40 booklets, it collects physical and digital instances of opinions and behaviours directed towards aging women and their bodies. The books are categorized into various body parts, presenting quotes, advertisements, social media posts, products, lyrics, etc. that highlight how we react to an aging, fem(ale)* anatomy. Come see part 2 at GradEx! \n\n*fem(ale)/women includes the shared experience of cis, afab trans, non-binary, agender/gender-nonconforming, and gender-variant people! ",
"bio": "Hi! I’m N’Dasa (pronounced en-day-sah) Todd, a GTA-based graphic designer interested in ephemera, archives, and publications. Being interested in visualizing archival data, a lot of my design collects instances of culture, identity, and memories, culminating in physical pieces that provide evidence of being. I hope to continue creating work that immortalizes the people and environments around me!",

"work_email": "nandinigandhi@ocadu.ca",
"project_name": "Seeing Sound - A Visual Simulation of Synesthesia",
"project_description": "This project simulates chromesthesia, a form of synesthesia where sound involuntarily evokes color, movement, and shape. Through real-time microphone input and audio analysis, the installation transforms live sound into visual form—allowing viewers to experience a sensory crossover that is usually internal and deeply personal. Color becomes responsive, fluid, and alive, shaped by the pitch, intensity, and complexity of surrounding sounds. Silence erases the image; noise gives it form.\n\nBy merging code with perception, this simulation offers a glimpse into a different way of sensing the world—where the boundary between hearing and seeing dissolves. It invites participants to consider how others experience reality, and how technology and design can bridge gaps in understanding what it means to feel, to sense, and to be. Graphic design is all about visual communication so in the end, I hope this doesn’t just simulate chromesthesia, I hope it creates a moment of empathy. A chance to see sound, not just hear it.",
"bio": "Hi, I'm Nandini! As a designer, my focus is on creating meaningful and impactful visual experiences through visual communication design, anchored in storytelling. My approach combines research, experimentation, and attention to detail, ensuring that my work is both functional and visually compelling. I am particularly drawn to the intersection of traditional design principles and emerging technologies, embracing innovation while respecting the foundations of design.",
"comments": "I think the video is better at representing the project!"
}

"email": "ruonc@ocadu.ca",
"name": "Ruon Hee Chon",
"modified_time": "",
"preferred_name": "Ruon Hee Chon",
"pronouns": "she/her;",
"website": "https://yunniejrh.wixsite.com/ruonhee-s-portfolio",
"social_media": "Instagram: @v.uni_ine.v\nYoutube: @yolhee4881",
"work_email": "yunniejrh@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Najeonchilgi Meets Canada – A Fusion of Cultural Storytelling",
"project_description": "This project explores the fusion of two distinct cultural identities—Korean najeonchilgi (mother-of-pearl inlay) and Canadian landscapes—through visual storytelling. Najeonchilgi is a traditional Korean craft known for its detailed floral patterns, symmetrical layouts, and iridescent textures set against black lacquered backgrounds. I reinterpreted this heritage technique digitally, applying its elements to Canadian landmarks like the CN Tower, Parliament Hill, and the Rocky Mountains.\n\nAs a Korean designer living in Canada, I aimed to reflect my personal experience of navigating two cultures. The project began with a series of digital posters that visually combine Korean decorative motifs with Canadian symbols. These posters were designed with symmetry and pastel tones on black backgrounds, evoking the elegance of najeonchilgi while introducing Canadian identity through landscapes and the beaver, Canada’s national animal.\n\nI printed the posters to explore materiality and tactility and created a handmade wooden box decorated in the same style. This box served as a tangible artifact, adding depth and texture to the project. The beaver character appears across both digital and physical outcomes, engaging in playful activities that connect cultural symbols with everyday life.\n\nThrough this work, I aimed to create a meaningful dialogue between Korean tradition and Canadian culture, showing how design can bridge histories and geographies in new and creative ways.",
"bio": "RuonHee Chon is a Korean graphic designer based in Toronto, Canada. Her work explores cultural storytelling by blending Korean traditional craft with modern design. Inspired by najeonchilgi (mother-of-pearl inlay), she creates visual experiences that connect her heritage with contemporary landscapes, focusing on themes of identity, place, and cultural fusion.",
"comments": ""
}

"work_email": "shovemiyap@gmail.com",
"project_name": "",
"project_description": "Fractured Frames is a multidisciplinary thesis project that explores the portrayal of female archetypes in neo-noir cinema from the 1970s to the 2000s. Through a graphic design lens, the project investigates how visual and narrative techniques in these films construct, mediate, and often aestheticize female suffering. The work critically examines how these portrayals reinforce or subvert cultural perceptions of gender, empathy, and power. This project aims to uncover the recurring roles women inhabit in neo-noir—such as the femme fatale, the victim, the damsel in distress, and the survivor—and how these archetypes evolve across decades. It reflects on how their suffering is stylized and framed within the cinematic language of darkness, ambiguity, and psychological tension characteristic of the genre.",
"bio": "Hi! I’m Shovemiya Packiyanathan, a graphic designer passionate about creating work through photography and design. Whether crafting visuals or capturing moments, I aim to create work that connects and inspires. I’m always eager to explore new ideas, take on exciting challenges, and showcase my unique perspective. I’d love for you to explore my work and see where creativity takes us!",
"comments": ""
}

"pronouns": "she/her;",
"website": "",
"social_media": "",
"work_email": "Simar03kaur@gmail.com",
"project_name": "IDCO ",
"project_description": "IDCO is a thesis project that critiques the commodification of identity in consumer culture through satire, irony, and exaggeration. It explores how products are no longer just objects, but are marketed as essential parts of who we are. At its core is a fictional e-commerce platform selling pre-packaged identities—because why go through self-discovery when you can just subscribe? The experience includes a personality quiz that strips away even the illusion of choice by telling users exactly who they should be, and an over-the-top brand guideline that explains the fabricated importance of IDCO’s logo and tone. Through this digital and physical ecosystem, IDCO invites viewers to question how consumerism turns meaningful experiences into marketable aesthetics—and what that means for our sense of self.\n\nYou can visit the website here: http://idco.space/",
"bio": "Simar Kaur is a graphic designer who graduated in 2025 from OCAD University in Toronto. With a natural curiosity and an eagerness to learn, she approaches each project with an open mind, continuously evolving her design style to meet the specific needs of every challenge. Rather than adhering to a fixed aesthetic, she embraces flexibility, blending various techniques and concepts to create designs that are both functional and visually engaging.\n\nFocused on the balance between form and function, Simar aims to craft designs that not only communicate a clear message but do so in a compelling and aesthetically pleasing way. Her work is rooted in the belief that effective visual communication transcends style, instead marrying purpose with beauty. Through each project, she strives to create meaningful connections between the audience and the message, ultimately enhancing the experience through thoughtful design.\n",
"comments": ""
}

  "project_description": "IDCO is a thesis project that critiques the commodification of identity in consumer culture through satire, irony, and exaggeration. It explores how products are no longer just objects, but are marketed as essential parts of who we are. At its core is a fictional e-commerce platform selling pre-packaged identities—because why go through self-discovery when you can just subscribe? The experience includes a personality quiz that strips away even the illusion of choice by telling users exactly who they should be, and an over-the-top brand guideline that explains the fabricated importance of IDCO’s logo and tone. Through this digital and physical ecosystem, IDCO invites viewers to question how consumerism turns meaningful experiences into marketable aesthetics—and what that means for our sense of self.\n\nYou can visit the website here: http://idco.space/",
  "bio": "Simar Kaur is a graphic designer who graduated in 2025 from OCAD University in Toronto. With a natural curiosity and an eagerness to learn, she approaches each project with an open mind, continuously evolving her design style to meet the specific needs of every challenge. Rather than adhering to a fixed aesthetic, she embraces flexibility, blending various techniques and concepts to create designs that are both functional and visually engaging.\n\nFocused on the balance between form and function, Simar aims to craft designs that not only communicate a clear message but do so in a compelling and aesthetically pleasing way. Her work is rooted in the belief that effective visual communication transcends style, instead marrying purpose with beauty. Through each project, she strives to create meaningful connections between the audience and the message, ultimately enhancing the experience through thoughtful design.\n",
  "comments": ""
}

"project_name": "Illusion of Choice",
"project_description": "“The Illusion of Choice” critically examines digital consent manipulation through everyday interfaces like CAPTCHAs, user agreements, and web cookies. Using satirical mixed-media animations, an intentionally frustrating interactive website, and a provocative poster, this project reveals the hidden coercion behind digital consent, encouraging users to question their online interactions and perceived autonomy. \n\n✦ Artifact 1: Animation + Accordion Zine\n\"A Cookie’s Journey\" is a looping mixed-media animation that follows a curious web cookie tracking user data across the internet. The accompanying accordion zine, packaged inside a cookie jar, unfolds the hidden layers of digital tracking in a playful, bilingual narrative.\n\n✦ Artifact 2: Interactive Website\n\"Illusion of Choice\" is an interactive website that recreates frustrating digital consent experiences through endless pop-ups, unsolvable CAPTCHAs, frustrating user agreements, and manipulative interfaces. It challenges users to confront the deceptive designs that pressure them into agreeing without real choice. \n\nhttps://simrankhanna484.github.io/illusion-of-choice/ \n\n✦ Artifact 3: Poster\nThe \"Illusion of Choice\" poster visually captures the core themes of the project. Mimicking digital cookies, it removes interactivity, forcing viewers to recognize the static, unavoidable nature of online consent and question the illusion of agency in digital spaces.\n",
"bio": "Simran Khanna is a Toronto-based graphic designer and multimedia artist whose work explores digital culture through interactive websites and mixed-media storytelling. Drawing from design innovation and visual satire, Simran’s practice creatively critiques contemporary digital experiences, inviting audiences to rethink their relationship with technology and the choices they encounter online.\n\nhttps://simrankhanna484.github.io/illusion-of-choice/ ",
"comments": ""
}

"modified_time": "",
"preferred_name": "Talea Tambakos",
"pronouns": "she/her;",
"website": "https://taleatambakos.myportfolio.com",
"social_media": "Instagram: @taleatambakos",
"work_email": "taleatambakos@gmail.com",
"project_name": "Graphic Design, Drawing and Painting",
"project_description": "I have many different projects that are unrelated as I am not in thesis, feel free to highlight only a few or them all, completely up to the format of this website. I have provided short descriptions for each, labeled in relation to the image names\n\nWork 1: Beyond the Frame is a collection of fifteen essays written by Talea Tambakos. Representing her evolution in design and academic critical discourse, all pieces are dated and ordered chronologically to invite the reader to observe improvements, notice mistakes, and most importantly, learn something new.\n\nWork 2: Design for Cannabis is a three-part publication series that explores the influence of design within the cannabis industry. Through Archive, Annotated Bibliography, and SketchUp for Interior Design, the series highlights the importance of design within a competitive market.\n\nWork 3: Untitled-1 becomes a memoir of Talea’s arts and design education within the past four years. By combining the technical appearance of the Photoshop window with a painted medium, this piece exhibits her love for both digital and traditional art and design.\n\nWork 4: Echos of Home is a self-reflective piece of Talea’s memories, nostalgia for childhood, and a longing for the happiness she felt while visiting her family’s home in Spathes, Greece.\n\nWork 5: This poster pair highlights Talea’s passion for examining the forms of human anatomy through detailed and scientifically labelled illustrations of the human skeletal and musculoskeletal systems.",
"bio": "Talea Tambakos is a Toronto-based graphic designer & artist.\nHer experience in both digital & traditional forms of art & design works to express her interest in typography, image manipulation, and illustration through multiple mediums. With a passion for studying the forms of human anatomy and themes within art historical discourse, her work remains diverse in subject yet visually and thematically intriguing.",
"comments": "Not sure the context of where the picture of me will appear. You can choose whichever one you think looks better for the context :)"
}

Essays on Art History & Visual Culture

39

THIRTEEN
13

Comparison of Hagia
Sophia (532-37 CE) &
The Great Mosque of
Cérdoba (784-987 CE)

10.12.2024

VISA - 3027 - 301
Professor Heather Coffey

References

Dodds, Jerrilynn. 1992. “The Great Mosque of
Cérdoba,” in Al-Andalus: The Art of Islamic Spain
(New York: Metropolitan Museum of Art), 11-25.

Ousterhout, Robert. “The Holy Space: Architecture

and Liturgy,” in Heaven and Earth: Art and the Church
in Byzantium, ed. Linda Safran, 81-120.

Beyond The Frame: Essays In Art History & Visual Cuture

Although originally built over two hundred years
apart and from different cultures, Hagia Sophia
(532-537 CE) (Fig. 13.1) and The Great Mosque of
Cérdoba (784-987 CE) (Fig. 13.2) share art-histor-
ical similarities and differences in historical influ-

nce, religi Istyle. Created
by architects Anthemius of Tralles and Isidorus
of Miletus in Constantinople, Hagia Sophia is an
extraordinary example of early Byzantine architec-
ture, becoming the source of influence for many
proceeding churches due to its uniquely colossal
size (Ousterhout, 82). “Some of the planning ideas
of Hagia Sophia find their way into later Byzantine
architecture..” (97) as itis the first to combine ele-
ments of both alongitudinally and centrally planned

131

such as the large circular Arabic emblems seen
in the image provided (83). Opposingly, The Great
Mosque was originally built as an Islamic mosque
which reflected the tradition of a wide space ..
that depended on repetition of a single support
to create a hall for community prayer” (Dodds
1992, 12). After Cérdoba became ruled by Ferdi-
nand Ill, the mosque was converted into a space
of Christian worship and a new cathedral which
disrupted the original flat prayer hall was built (24).
The ornamental aspects of the mosque seem
rather plain within the interior compared to Hagia
Sophia, which contained images of iconography,
but detailed, anthropomorphic implications at the
exterior outshine the exterior of Hagia Sophia. Both

space. Alternatively, the main cong

of The Great Mosque of Crdoba, constructed orig-

inally by Abd al-Rahman | exhibits the opposite

effect of influence, becoming a successful continu-

ation of existing el ts of traditi ilding tra-

ditions of Muslim-dominated Spain (Dodds 1992,
i

are strategically constructed to house
theirintended religious worshiping practices, which
were then modified to suit alternative religions.
The interiors of both architectural marvels are
vastly different, yet the use of space is a notably
fluid theme. The massive size of Hagia Sophia’s

simple inits interior decorative elements, introduc-
ing only a two-toned pattern in alternating brick
and stone material to form the horseshoe-shaped
arches within the space. There is a structurally
similar incorporation of columns to that of Hagia
Sophia in which the “..prayer hall roof is supported
by columns sustaining ten arcades of 12 bays each,
including a central aisle..” (Dodds 1992, 12), yet
the mosque becomes most notable for its remark-
able boundless appearance, which is achieved
through the buildings horizontal and flat expanse.
Both examples of architecture underwent recon-
structions and additions to the spaces, but each
for different reasons and at alternate timelines.
The original dome of Hagia Sophia collapsed in
557 CE due to structural problems and deforma-
tions, and the building was ruined after the riot
of the Nika Rebellion (Ousterhout, 82, 90). How-
ever, the reconstruction was completed fairly
quickly, compared to the development of The

Great Mosque which did not suffer devastation
b

13).Th
of Indigenous elements and spolia in the form of
columns from ruined Roman buildings. Neverthe-
less, both structures are iconic symbols of their
creators’ cultural architecture, each being the first
of their kind, either expressing a unique size or
an outstanding reflection of traditional methods.
Hagia Sophia and The Great Mosque symbolize
an overlap of cultures through physical and func-
tional means. Originally constructed as a Christian
cathedral, the interior of Hagia Sophia features
a meeting hall that hosted large communal wor-
ship congregations (Ousterhout, 88). During the
Ottoman period, the structure was converted
into a mosque, resulting in the inclusion of four
minarets seen at the exterior view and additions

ntrally posi d, hundred-footdome

ut ly added to through phases intro-

the nave to stand at a hundred-and-eighty feet high,
supported by pendentives (Ousterhout, 82). How
this dome is composed, with the additions of the
light imposed by the clerestory, contributes to a

i f the heavy iality and
is the key elementin the building’s expansive reach
vertically. The viewer's eye is moved away from the
thick cement walls towards the central dome, work-
ing with the monograms found in the capital stands
of the pillars that support the dome to create adis-
traction from the structural flaws and sheer weight
ofthe building's cementwalls. Itappears that Hagia
Sophia seeks to distract the viewer from the mate-
riality of the building, while the mosque invites the
viewer to recognize it. The mosque remains fairly

duced by different rulers. The comparison and
contrast of Hagia Sophia and The Great Mosque
of Cérdoba provides an example of the variety of
structural opportunities that existed in the con-
struction of religious spaces within the Medieval
period, while simultaneously existing as extraor-
dinary marvels of architectural design and layout.

"project_name": "",
"project_description": "My exhibition will be of a publication and an interactive exhibition diving into the story of a selected woman in science who faced prejudice all her life. The exhibit will showcase aspects of all the ways this prejudice was present in their life. The publication highlights the extraordinary journeys of ten pioneering women who broke barriers and reshaped the landscape of science. In fields traditionally dominated by men, these remarkable women faced discrimination, dismissal, and a persistent lack of recognition, yet they endured. Their stories are shared to honour their resilience, shed light on their achievements, and ensure their legacies are never forgotten. My intention with this project was to amplify the voices of women. ",
"bio": "I’m a graphic designer with a strong curiosity for biology—an unlikely duo that fuels my creative process in unexpected ways. I enjoy exploring all facets of art, from analog techniques to photography and beyond. I thrive on a challenge and am constantly learning, driven in part by an admittedly bold (but well-placed) confidence that I can master any form of design I set my mind to.",
"comments": "*my portfolio is under construction there's changes that need to be made so if it's possible to not make my post till at least the end of this week, I'd really appreciate it!"
}
